COMPONENT NAME: IKM JDE World Control Append
AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION: - Integration Knowledge Module - Integrates data into JDE World Z-table in control append mode. - Data can be checked using a CKM. Invalid data are isolated in the Error Table and can be recycled. - The KM performs Integration into JDE World with a Dream Writer batch traitment.
RESTRICTIONS: - This IKM only works with standard IBM DB2 iSeries JDBC Driver, i.e. the target JDE World Z-table has to be reversed through standard IBM DB2 iSeries JDBC Driver, not JDE World JDBC Driver. - When using the RECYCLE_ERRORS option, you have to set an Update Key for your interface. - When using this module with a journalized source table, data is automatically filtered to not include source deletions. - The FLOW_CONTROL and STATIC_CONTROL options call the Check Knowledge Module to isolate invalid data (if no CKM is set, an error occurs).
Automatically attempts to insert data into the Target Datastore of the Interface.
Identifies and updates rows of the Target Datastore depending on the value of the UPDATE_KEY columns of the target datastore records.
Check this option to synchronize journalized deletions. This option will take effect only if one source table is journalized in your interface
Uncheck this option if you do not want to perform a flow control
Check this option to recycle data rejected by flow control in a previous execution of this interface.
Check this option to control the target table after having inserted or updated target data.
Check this option if you want to delete all the rows of the target datastore.
Check this option if you want to create the target table
Uncheck this option if you want to keep the integration table in the work area after the execution. Useful for debugging
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
Check this option to invoke the RPG program
The name of the version of the report that you want to duplicate and process

Check this box if you want to use a security file for JDE connection information.
If checked: -the JDE_SECURITY_FILE option must be set and refere to a file accessible from ODI. -the options JDE_USER,JDE_PASSWORD,JDE_ENVIRONMENT,JDE_ADDRESS are ignored and should not be set
If not checked -the options JDE_USER,JDE_PASSWORD,JDE_ENVIRONMENT,JDE_ADDRESS are mandatory
Full path to JDE security file

If the option USE_SECURITY_FILE is checked: This option must be set and point to the file that store the JDE connection information For security raison, this file should be store in a safe place, but accessible by ODI The format of the file is
# This file describes the JDE connection information # Username=jde_username Password=jde_password Environment=jde_environment Address=jde_server_address
If the option USE_SECURITY_FILE is not checked: This option is ignored

conn = WorldConnection.getJdbcConnection(user) inputs = jarray.array(["Y",KCO,EDTN],java.lang.String ) version=WorldTemporaryVersion(programName,version2Cpy, conn) versionName = version.getTemporaryVersion(inputs)
